{"cursor":"19669","size":14,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":" outside the Castle Rock microbrewery in Nottingham, England.]]\n\n\nA 'microbrewery' is a brewery which produces a limited amount of\nbeer.\n\nIn the UK, the term has become synonymous with small scale breweries operating\nunder the UK Progressive Beer Duty threshold of 5,000 hls. The most common\nproduct is cask conditioned bitter. Breweries are often described by their\nproduction capacity or brew length, mostly ranging from 2 to 20 bbls (a brewer's\nbarrel or bbl is 36 imperial gallons).\n\nIn the US, the American Brewers Association defines a \"craft brewery\" as \"small,\nindependent and traditional\", and gives a production size of less than a year\nand can not be more than 24% owned by another alcoholic beverage company that is\nnot itself a craft brewery (This means Goose Island and other breweries like it\nare no longer craft breweries due to ownership by MillerCoors or Anheuser-\nBusch). A brewpub may also be known as a microbrewery if production\nhas a significant distribution beyond the premises - the American Brewers\nAssociation use a fixed 75% of production to determine if a company is a\nmicrobrewery.; regional craft brewery: at\nleast 50% of its volume is all malt beers.\nA regional brewery has annual production between and per year. In order to be\nclassified as a \"regional craft brewery\" by the brewers association, a brewery\nmust possess \"either an all-malt flagship or [have] at least 50% of its volume\nin either all-malt beers or in beers which use adjuncts to enhance rather than\nlighten flavor.\" Of the 2,126 breweries\nin America, only 43 are not defined as craft brewers, and 100 not defined as\neither a micro or brewpub.\n","linknr":349,"url":"Microbrewery","recorded":1363453070,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Microbrewery&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Microbrewery&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/op